r at times\".\n She explained: \"At his best, in books like The Executioner's Song, he could be a really fine stylist, when he reined himself in. But the problem was his inability to rein himself in life was sometimes mirrored on the page.\"\n First broadcast on BBC Radio 4's Today programme on Thursday 7 November 2013.","feed":null,"feeds":null,"favicon":"http://www.bbc.co.uk/favicon.ico","description":"Mike Lennon, author of Norman Mailer: A Double Life, and Sarah Churchwell, professor of American literature at the University of East Anglia, debate Norman Mailer's success as a writer.","datetime":"2013-11-07 12:00:00 +0000"}
